1:# Recipe 6.2: Utilization Pattern Segmentation (Python Example)
9:## Setup
27:## Config and Constants
46:# Structured logging. Never log member IDs or PHI in production.
50:# Retry config for AWS API calls.
53:# boto3 clients (module-level for Lambda container reuse).
57:# --- Feature Configuration ---
59:# These are the utilization dimensions we cluster on.
60:# Each feature captures a different aspect of how a member uses healthcare.
61:# The choice of features is the single most important design decision in this
62:# pipeline. Get these wrong and your segments will be meaningless.
74:# --- Clustering Configuration ---
76:# Number of segments to discover. 4-6 is typical for utilization segmentation.
77:# Too few and you lose actionable distinctions. Too many and care managers
78:# can't design distinct interventions for each segment.
81:# Random seed for reproducibility. KMeans initialization is stochastic;
82:# setting this ensures you get the same segments on repeated runs with
83:# the same data. Change it when you want to explore alternative solutions.
86:# --- Segment Labels ---
87:# After clustering, we assign human-readable labels based on the centroid
88:# characteristics. These are the labels population health teams actually use.
89:# The mapping from cluster number to label happens in the interpretation step.
98:# --- Infrastructure ---
